english:
  title: Snow on New Year's Day
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Snow falls through the last night of the year and reaches New Year's dawn,
    Only to melt away helpless beneath the breath of spring wind.
    The twin palace gates grow dim in shadow,
    Yet leather boots already echo across the Five Gate Bridge.
    Let the officials' robes grow wet in the morning audience—
    It suits the dancing sleeves of court ladies swaying.
    Since this new year brings such auspicious signs,
    I offer spiced wine and folk songs for all the people.
  footnotes:
    - The Five Gate Bridge (五門橋) refers to the main approaches to the royal palace where official ceremonies took place.
    - The 'spiced wine' (椒柏酒) was traditionally made with pepper and cypress leaves, a ceremonial drink offered during New Year celebrations.
    - The poem contrasts the melting snow—a harbinger of spring—with the formal New Year court ceremony, suggesting both the natural renewal of seasons and the human rituals of governance.
